Title: Hillbilly Elegy: A Memoir of a Family and Culture in Crisis
Author: J.D. Vance
My Review:
Absolutely stunning.

I expected much more political, racial, and socioeconomic analysis than is presented, but was pleasantly surprised by the lack thereof. Vance entirely succeeds in introducing and humanizing a group and culture that are often marginalized or even explicitly objectified (white trash, anyone?).

I have spent the majority of my life interacting with the Pacific Northwest version of this story in an economically-troubled logging town in Washington; the similarities in narrative and outcomes are haunting and tragic. Vance excels in crafting a cohesive narrative rather than an argument -- though the book achieves both functions -- and its intensely personal nature removes any perception of political positioning, despite specific statements revealing political leanings.

I read this during one caffeine-fueled focus binge, revealing both the book's inherent readability and optimal length as well as the extent to which reading is tearing my schedule apart in a dubiously beneficial process of cathartic sleep deprivation.

Read this book; you will not regret it.

Title: The New Jim Crow: Mass Incarceration in the Age of Colorblindness
Author: Michelle Alexander
My Review:
This was a challenging book to read because of how unbelievable - but true - it is. I am shook. I realize now that almost everything I've said about our criminal justice system was ignorant and/or uninformed. What hits me hardest is that it is explicitly legal to racially profile in policing, that prosecutors have no check on their power, and that the current law-and-order environment will likely preempt any efforts in the near-to-intermediate future to solve these problems or end the drug war that is at their root. Black lives matter; I feel so much more sure about that now.
Now, on to the next couple books. #attampttogetwoke2k17

Title: The Autobiography of Gucci Mane
Author: Gucci Mane
My Review:
No other book has made me listen to all of Gucci Mane's mixtapes like this has.

...but seriously, this is how a modern memoir should be: gripping, personal, honest, narrative-focused, self-aware, and short. Let's get real, famous people: nobody wants to read a long book about your life. In this we don't hear about the gnarly details because he knows we don't really care; we just hear the story of a life.

Most of all, Gucci Mane reveals that he is just a human, albeit one who happens to be a famous rich criminally prolific rapper. He has an ego; he is often hypocritical; his relationships are a rollercoaster of disappointment, abandonment, and reconciliation; he's ashamed of his mistakes and personal failings. He's unabashedly proud of his hard work and his beautiful woman. This reads more like a journal entry or a campfire story than an edited, commercially approved autobiography.

We need more memoirs like this -- preferably that make me want to listen to Gucci Mane's mixtapes.

Definitely do the audiobook.

Title: Sex at Dawn: The Prehistoric Origins of Modern Sexuality
Author: Christopher  Ryan
My Review: I loved most of this book, especially the beginning and the end. The middle rambled a bit with anthropological stuff that I found neither interesting nor relevant. But overall anyone who prefers to approach the subject of human sexuality from a realistic, scientific perspective will appreciate this book, regardless of prior belief. The authors pursue the argument that humans are not monogamous creatures from an evolutionary perspective. Physiologically, psychologically, and culturally, humans have never been monogamous and probably never will be - regardless of how much we try to convince ourselves that we should be based on current religious or cultural expectations. The last 25% of the book and especially its discussion of physiological factors is the best part - humorous, engaging, and (like the rest of the book) very tongue-in-cheek.

Title: Thanks, Obama: My Hopey, Changey White House Years
Author: David Litt
My Review:
Some great laughs, but painful to read as Litt follows the same formula again and again: he thought something was going [great / terribly] but suddenly it turned out that it was actually [terrible / great] and it [unalterably decreases his self-worth / makes his low self-worth feel more balanced] but it turned out to be alright in the end. A bit heavy on the snark -- sometimes to great humorous effect -- and a bit lean on the substance.

Great love story with David and Jackie.

I like that Litt doesn't try to take credit for things he didn't do, and makes sure people know that he was a White House staffer who wasn't particularly close to the POTUS for most of his tenure.

I like Obama's narrative more than Litt's. We get a picture of who Obama was to the people he worked with. I feel like I understand how the White House works/worked.

Glad to have read it, but I wouldn't call it a gem.

Title: Brave New World
Author: Aldous Huxley
My Review:
Historical impact: 10
My personal enjoyment reading it: 4

This is no fun at all, not even for literature value. I get that it served as a dystopian/utopian metaphorical warning for the horrors of life in a "perfect" society. I get that it is eighty years old and therefore I should temper my expectations for its diction.

That being said, Bernard Marx is a terrible main character who easily abandons his principles; Helmholtz Watson, supposed confidant and comrade to Marx, uselessly prattles about art, doesn't act like a real person, but suddenly joins the Savage in his "heroic" final action; John the Savage, a supposed foil for what modern civilization has become, isn't introduced until halfway through. The universal love interest adds nothing to the story.

I must add that my favorite character/the only character I like is Mustapha Mond, World Controller and, like Marx, hypocritical abandoner of principles who rules over a world he initially sought to transcend and which he had the opportunity to leave. I like him because his John Galt-esque speech was the only part of the story that actually contained any gripping story. I understood his character. His choices, which I detest, make sense in the context of his role in society. I hate him, but I appreciate his presence. Other than him, though, the characters and plot never approach the completeness of the themes they develop.

Maybe this is the point of the story: as the reader I SHOULD hate the characters. Maybe the half-formed heroes, the well-conditioned love interest, the painful social sensitivity, the success of the society's conditioning are deliberate casualties of the real message -- that fully embracing modern industrial production a la Henry Ford (excellent replacement of f*** with Ford) leads to false happiness, libertine sexual values, the destruction of the family, blatant social stratification by GMO human production and behavioural conditioning -- and thus maybe I should try harder to appreciate them.

In that frame, there exists irony in my hating the story -- the characters, plot, etc. -- strictly BECAUSE the underlying thesis is successful.

However, the frame through which I read any book requires those factors to be as well-formed as the themes. Therefore I disliked reading this partially-finished, seemingly unedited alarmist bile that lacked any sort of literary depth.

Sue me.

Title: Slavery by Another Name: The Re-Enslavement of Black Americans from the Civil War to World War II
Author: Douglas A. Blackmon
My Review:
I really like that Blackmon chooses a narrow frame of analysis to explain what happened on a much wider range. His exploration of the Cottenham family's history and historical context is excellent and thorough, as is his description of the events of the time period. I wanted to learn about what happened to black Americans after emancipation, and this book paints a vivid picture of the stark realities of the time for that group.

However, I feel that the book was a bit repetitive in its descriptions of specific circumstances, and though I understand that the author did this in hopes of reinforcing his thesis, he often goes a little too far in that attempt.

Overall a good read but perhaps unnecessary if you can find a more concise description of the events and circumstances of the time period.

Note: I appreciate that Blackmon stays focused on description of the events and their coincident implications, rather than straying to speculate about those events' implications on the racial and class issues of the present. What he describes does have strong implications in the present, of course, but to make them a point of focus in the book would have been very distracting for the reader and would have muddled the book's thesis.

Title: The Lost City of the Monkey God: A True Story
Author: Douglas Preston
My Review:
A gripping tale, well-told.

Preston skillfully integrates the legend of the lost city, the story of the long path to the expeditions, the personal and archaeological details of the trips, and the political and academic environment surrounding the expedition with the real overarching basis that 500 years ago enabled the whole venture: European diseases had a massively fatal effect on pre-Colombian South American civilizations. The rediscovered cities were abandoned after successive pandemics wiped out most of their populations, and the cities' serendipitous locations in impenetrable jungle preserved the sites.

Preston's description of his own harrowing experience with the leishmaniasis parasite is moving. I appreciate the admission of historical irony: old world explorers struck by new world diseases upon entering new world cities previously wiped out by old world diseases.

I couldn't put this book down when I started reading it. Highly recommend.

Title: Inhuman Bondage: The Rise and Fall of Slavery in the New World
Author: David Brion Davis
My Review:
I wanted a book about the history of slavery that balanced depth of research with breadth of scope - not long and boring, but not a cursory overview. This book filled this requirement. Davis moves through the history of the institution of slavery without boring the reader. I am impressed and feel a bit more educated, and therefore am satisfied.

(Note: This is the second book I've read in an attempt to learn more about the history of race in the US. If you are reading this and want to recommend another, please recommend one. Thx!)

Title: Mistakes Were Made (But Not by Me): Why We Justify Foolish Beliefs, Bad Decisions, and Hurtful Acts
Author: Carol Tavris
My Review:
I reread this for the third time as it's UI's common read this year. I had the pleasure of being on the book selection committee and somehow this book, my nomination, was selected. I'll have the privilege to introduce author Carol Tavris next week at the common read lecture.
I first read this 2 years ago and it dramatically changed how I think about why I think what I think and why I do what I do. We all self-justify to avoid the painful dissonance we create; this helps us stay happy and content, but it also leads us to deceive ourselves and can have massive negative impacts on society. When we become more aware of how we handle dissonance and where that dissonance exists in our lives, it can be extremely uncomfortable - but it's so necessary to accept that dissonance, work through it, and move on.
My main takeaway: we need to remain critically uncomfortable with ourselves in order to be up front with our flaws and mistakes. only then can we transcend them.

I feel that the life-changing part of the magic of tidying is being deliberate about what you own and especially giving thanks not FOR the things you own but TO the things you own. This book is explicitly materialist in nature, but the idea giving thanks to things brings its focus into a higher realm of sorts. That said, I do not like how Marie beat her 100% success rate into the ground, as it seems unrealistic. Much of the rest of the content is specific in the vein of other self-help books that I have a hard time enjoying. Good overall for the good stuff; I'll try to ignore the rest.
Thank you, book, for helping me get through a few dozen miles of running in cold weather.

Title: Atlas Shrugged
Author: Ayn Rand
My Review:
I liked this book more than any other book that I've rated as 4 stars. The characters, settings, and plotlines pulled me in and kept me coming back for more. The philosophy behind it was my favorite aspect, however, and was the reason I read the book in the first place.
During the first half of the book, I thought, "Wow! Objectivism is a great philosophy that emphasizes personal effort and maximum return on effort! And you have to be honest with yourself about everything and ponder the reasons you do things and not uphold stupid societal strictures if you don't believe in them!"
And then in the second half of the book, I thought, "Wow! None of objectivism's representative heroes have the ability to feel anything, unless they are together reveling in each other's selfishness! This philosophy fails to recognize the personal return to charity, and is more anarcho-capitalism than individualism!"
Basically I got sick of having people defined as binary, having every heroic moment accompanied by a lack of emotion, having women unable to enjoy relationships unless they feel like a male's sex servant, and of philosophers entirely abandoning those who don't perfectly share their belief.
The story admittedly jumps randomly to new focuses (e.g. finding the engine, the hobo on the train working at 20th Century, being close to an airport when the train gets stuck) and the discontinuity gets a bit old. Some characters exist only to emphasize a belief without necessarily being important to the story (Cheryl, Stadler). Galt's radio speech was pretty incomprehensible, and I had a hard time focusing on it.

But overlooking those obvious flaws, I did enjoy this book. A lot. It combines my love of philosophy, books, and controversial ideas in a very good package. But I can't let the story's discontinuity and repetitive characterizations get by without a star deduction.

My Review:
I enjoyed this book immensely. When I read Malcolm Gladwell's other books, his writing style gets a little old. This book doesn't suffer from that problem because the topics are so varied and only about 25 pages each.
This book showcases what Gladwell is best at, putting a new twist on an old subject or bringing an obscure topic to light in an interesting and accessible way. The best thing is that the book feels like several short books in one, and because I love short books, I love this book.

Just another "these people repressed their natural urges and lived terribly unhappy lives overall and they happened to be happy and successful and so we could do the same and maybe have the same results" kind of book, except this book has a lot more detail and is not really a self-help book as much as it is a series of somewhat depressing case studies. Title: But What If We're Wrong? Thinking About the Present As If It Were the Past
Author: Chuck Klosterman
My Review:
Why dismiss crazy ideas offhand without rational consideration? But What If We're Wrong explores various ways this question applies to how future societies will construct their histories of the current period.

I love the endless consideration of potential outcomes, even taking seriously crazy-ish ideas. I love how Klosterman takes every idea down to its basic principle and actually delves into how history is created/remembered regardless of the reality. If you've read the blog-ish site Wait But Why, written by Tim Urban (I highly, highly, highly, highly recommend WBW), then you'll be familiar with the writing style: sarcastic, thorough, intellectually-informed analysis from a very personal perspective. The book can be dense and rambling at points, but it is a function of the medium and not at all a flaw.

Overall, a thoroughly enjoyable read.

Title: How to Get Filthy Rich in Rising Asia
Author: Mohsin Hamid
My Review:
Yes, this is a quick read, but that does not stop it from being powerful. In two hours surrounding a delicious breakfast of eggs, chicken, a bagel, and a spinach shake, I experienced true and deep catharsis.

The stark prose and ambiguity surrounding every character, setting and plot development left room for me as the reader to project my own emotions and experiences onto the story and especially onto the main character. I felt, viscerally, both the optimistic joy of success and the intense longing for lost love. That the story is told from the second-person only reinforces this incredible connection between reader and story.

As a skeptic of all forms of self help, I enjoyed the satirical self-help framework. I also applaud that it fails -- and that the narrator is fully conscious and upfront about that failure.

I don't cry often, and never due to books or movies. But at the end, which arrived far too soon, I cried, just absolutely sobbing with wistful happiness at experiencing a full life outside my own -- birth, love, struggle, death -- and it was all very confusing for a young, usually-stoic male raised in a masculinity-crazed society.

I found this book to be exceptional.
10/10, would recommend.

Side note: I read this book based on a recommendation from venture capitalist Chris Sacca in Tim Ferris's podcast. Apparently Sacca assigns it as required reading for startup founders at companies in which he invests.

Title: Human Transit: How Clearer Thinking about Public Transit Can Enrich Our Communities and Our Lives
Author: Jarrett Walker
My Review:
There's a reason this book was cited frequently in three of the books I've read recently about urban planning: it contains the dense, focused information of a textbook while maintaining Gladwell-esque readability. The book even includes many pictures and maps to emphasize points and serve as examples, enhancing my understanding.
Walker aptly displays why he's a sought-after transit consultant.
Refreshingly, he takes the viewpoint of an economist on transit planning: there is no good nor bad, just tradeoffs. Rather than present options as being one of opposite extremes, he describes each tradeoff as some point between the two extremes, on a spectrum.
Walker repeatedly emphasizes that the goal of the transit (some combination of Ridership or Coverage) creates the basis for planning; this helps remove all the typical "I'm successful, I'm the author, my way is best" egoism that plagues some similar books.
Overall, a concise guide to transit planning and relevant for anyone interested in the subject at any level. Kudos!

Title: What Doctors Feel: How Emotions Affect the Practice of Medicine
Author: Danielle Ofri
My Review:
Struggled to get though this book at certain points because of the drawn out emotional descriptions. Nonetheless, most descriptions are absolutely touching, especially patients' stories and the descriptions of the challenges doctors face in attempting to remain objective.
Perhaps my favorite sections describe the overwhelming responsibility doctors are expected to take in stride and how frustrated and jaded they become faced with such unreasonable expectations. I've experienced this secondhand watching my dad struggle with a crazy amount of work and stress in the name of providing the best possible care for his patients. I also really enjoyed Ofri's commentary regarding and analysis of the effects of America's bloated administrative and malpractice culture within medicine and its effects on patient care and rising costs.
Ofri stays true to her title and subtitle the entire book -- a rarity among today's nonfiction output.
Overall, I deeply enjoyed reading this book, and wish my pre-med friends the best of luck (eek). Star knocked for descriptions I could not get through.

Title: The Undoing Project: A Friendship That Changed Our Minds
Author: Michael   Lewis
My Review:
I'm a big fan of Michael Lewis' writing, but this book didn't quite match up. I felt that he beat the dead horse with personality descriptions of Amos and Danny without offering enough substance into their research and how those findings have affected the world.
I realize that this book is supposed to be a story of the two individuals, and it does okay in this regard. However, I really feel that Lewis doesn't do enough to substantiate the pair's impact.
This may be because I've read Kahneman's excellent Thinking, Fast and Slow, as well as a lot of other material describing their impact. But the feeling remains, and I'm left feeling a bit incomplete.
Major props to Lewis, however, for remaining objective much of his analysis and storytelling -- he does not portray Amos or Danny as perfect heroes or anything.

Title: Deep Economy: The Wealth of Communities and the Durable Future
Author: Bill McKibben
My Review:
Forced myself to finish this book. Though I fundamentally agree with the necessity of the problems that McKibben states, you can't just will people into being more community-centric and local, etc. The book talks a lot about the problems we face and the things we may need to do (in very general terms), but it does not realistically consider the downsides of such things or the political realities we would need to overcome to achieve these things.
I read this book to try to think more about economic thinking outside the mainstream, but I was disappointed by the author's unwillingness to realistically consider what would be needed to make the changes and the negative (instead of just the positive) effects.

My Review:
I enjoyed that Duhigg breaks the science of habit into its component parts: how it is formed, how it affects us, and how we can change them. The storytelling and writing are compelling and coherent.
That being said, the short-section format got old about halfway through the book, and the section on social habits was entirely unconvincing; it seemed that he was trying to pull some loose ends together to somehow throw together a section on social habits.
Overall, though, interesting read, would recommend to people interested in behavioral science.

Author: Orson Scott Card

Title: Fahrenheit 451
Author: Ray Bradbury
My Review: My favorite book when I was a sophomore in high school. It was eye-opening to see the similarities between Montag's world and mine. The book was really the first time that literature had made me wonder about my own life.

Title: The Perks of Being a Wallflower
Author: Stephen Chbosky

Title: How to Win Friends and Influence People
Author: Dale Carnegie

Title: The Best American Essays 1987
Author: Gay Talese

Title: White Noise
Author: Don DeLillo

Title: Excellent Sheep: The Miseducation of the American Elite and the Way to a Meaningful Life
Author: William Deresiewicz
My Review: Excellent Sheep is a compelling case for a liberal arts education and a reform of the higher education system. It is more opinion based than fact based but still remains mostly objective. Lots of good personal stories and examples are included. I feel like the book discounts the intensity of an Ivy League education and makes it sound like the cheap state school is as good an option as Yale. While this can be argued, it is hard to believe. The author does a good job of highlighting specific struggles that students face in top tier schools. Although the title says it includes the way to a more meaningful life, there are few definite prescriptive methods to improve the current state except to get a liberal arts education and change focus from success to true education.

Title: How to Win at College: Surprising Secrets for Success from the Country's Top Students
Author: Cal Newport
My Review: Vague, boringly positive take on surviving at college. Despite this, it does have some great suggestions for things to do to help a student succeed. While many are good, there are  several that seem to be a bit on the extreme side. As a college student, I have been trying some of them out and they've done well. There are 75 suggestions, and I narrowed them down to 32 that I could actually try to use. Of these, I've tried 9 so far and have found success with 6 of those. It's a great book if it is taken in an experimental perspective, not just a back-patting self-congratulatory fling.

Title: Banana: The Fate of the Fruit That Changed the World
Author: Dan Koeppel

Title: Smartcuts: How Hackers, Innovators, and Icons Accelerate Success
Author: Shane Snow
My Review: Smartcuts is very smart, very intelligent, and somewhat redundant. Snow is very good at weaving stories together  that seem to lead up to a great point, but might be better as a collection of stories about innovative people. He writes like Gladwell, but is much more interesting. I give this book four stars because of the excellent storytelling and several good ideas, like the image of surfers finding a wave to explain how Skrillex's timing in the music industry was so perfect.

Title: The Know-It-All: One Man's Humble Quest to Become the Smartest Person in the World
Author: A.J. Jacobs
My Review: Despite Jacobs' constant back-patting, I can't deny that I really enjoyed this book. Its unique alphabetized structure and never ending stream of interesting facts and wittiness had me engaged for all 369 pages. A heart warming tale mixed in about his and his wife's attempts to get pregnant helps too. Great read.

Title: Battle Hymn of the Tiger Mother
Author: Amy Chua
My Review: A painfully honest story of a mom's quest to make her kids as good as possible. I often wish that my parents had driven me as hard as Amy Chua drove Sophia and Lulu. It's nice to hear a non-defensive version of dedicated, driven parenting. I can definitely see why people can be taken aback by the book though.

Title: We Wish to Inform You That Tomorrow We Will Be Killed with Our Families
Author: Philip Gourevitch
My Review: Absolutely amazing. Touching, poignant, gripping, and concise. Clear record of events in Rwanda and surroundings before, after, and during genocide juxtaposed with philosophy of the human condition. Also a strong indictment of the international community for ignoring events and even supporting crimes against humanity. Eye-opening overall.

Title: Thinking, Fast and Slow
Author: Daniel Kahneman
My Review: A lot to take in. Excellent. I've read most of it twice now and I learn more every time I open it. Fabulous.

Title: Mistakes Were Made (But Not by Me): Why We Justify Foolish Beliefs, Bad Decisions, and Hurtful Acts
Author: Carol Tavris
My Review: This is the most marvelous book I have read this year. It is honest, focus, and personally poignant. Unlike most nonfiction books, this is both interesting and relevant: learning about how self-justification influences you can change how you think, feel and act. After reading, I feel a greater understanding of how my brain works and a better mindset for future actions and introspection. Excellent book. The current pinnacle of psychology books that I have read.

Title: How Google Works
Author: Eric Schmidt
My Review: Wow! This book is the best business book I've read in a while! I love the idea of the empowered smart creative, untethered by role or seniority, contributing in whatever way he sees fit. That's the type of person I want to be.

Title: When to Rob a Bank
Author: Steven D. Levitt
My Review: This book was a lot of fun. Sometimes, I get bored when a book rambles on and on about the same thing over and over again. Fortunately, reading this never offers a dull or repetitive moment. The writing is witty, intelligent, and usually very interesting. Would recommend, much.

Title: How to Fail at Almost Everything and Still Win Big: Kind of the Story of My Life
Author: Scott Adams
My Review: Loved this. Would recommend.

Title: Dead Aid: Why Aid Is Not Working and How There Is a Better Way for Africa
Author: Dambisa Moyo
My Review: Concise, comprehensive, and sagacious, Moyo says in only 154 pages what should've been said (and implemented) years ago by the massive international institutions responsible for facilitating sustainable development. Thank you, Zambian economist working for Goldman Sachs, for giving me the chance to use the word "sagacious."

Title: Narconomics: How to Run a Drug Cartel
Author: Tom Wainwright
My Review: An absolutely fascinating work of investigative journalism. Wainwright took pretty scary personal risks to bring us this rigorous description of the economics of drug cartels, how they function, and - by extension - how to weaken their financial, political, and geographic strength.

Title: Street Smart: The Rise of Cities and the Fall of Cars
Author: Samuel I. Schwartz
My Review:
A much more memoir-ish book containing viewpoints from the former head of NYC's transportation department. A lot of interesting stuff that is more macro than the streets-, development-, spaces-, or transit-specific books I have read recently. However, because it is only 250 pages long, it takes more of a jack of all trades, master of none approach. The things he does cover are great, though, especially regarding the way we think about streets and cities, and devious tales from Schwartz's time in city government.
Uses the word 'literally' far too often.

Title: The Glass Castle
Author: Jeannette Walls

Title: Ego Is the Enemy
Author: Ryan Holiday
My Review: An excellent source of wise quotes from ancient philosophers, and wise itself, if liberal in its use of anecdotal evidence. Good basic premise, though: whatever success you achieve, it will be because of your work and in spite of your ego; therefore you should minimize ego in order to maximize your work and therefore achieve even greater success.

Title: Modern Romance
Author: Aziz Ansari
My Review: What a fantastic book! It is pretty much a very extended version of every article I've ever seen about modern dating culture, and it is well worth the six-ish hours it takes to get through. I really love all the little factoids you can pick up during it. Aziz's describes his research well and skillfully weaves in a lot of personal narrative as well. Very enjoyable overall, a good quick read.

Author: Mark Di Vincenzo

Title: You Are a Badass: How to Stop Doubting Your Greatness and Start Living an Awesome Life
Author: Jen Sincero
My Review: Jen Sincero is somewhat sincere, but mostly just kind of inspirational. I'm sure her ideas have some sort of effect on some people, but they were pretty floofy. For example: "[You should buy an expensive car because owning it will make you feel like you deserve it, and it will motivate you to make money like you deserve it.]." Like I said before, it feels good to hear, but in practice, a lot of the ideas are a little crazy.

Title: Gung Ho!: Turn on the People in Any Organization
Author: Kenneth H. Blanchard
My Review: Overall, meh. While the tips laid out are decent, there is a six-page bulleted summary at the end from pages 135-140 that is really all you need. The story is heartwarming and all, but it is very cheesy and kind of pointless. Just look up a summary, unless you get the book for free.

Title: The Marshmallow Test: Mastering Self-Control
Author: Walter Mischel
My Review: Fascinating, if wandering. But mostly fascinating.

Title: Walkable City: How Downtown Can Save America, One Step at a Time
Author: Jeff Speck
My Review: Excellent information and extremely readable for a layperson like myself. It only fuels my curiosity about urban design and walkability. Now, onto more dense tomes about urban utility logistics!

Title: Happy City: Transforming Our Lives Through Urban Design
Author: Charles Montgomery
My Review: I really loved the skillfully woven narrative of this book. Unlike many books about urban design, it didn't offer much in the way of specific solutions. Instead, it offered a quick glance into many different aspects of how better urban planning can benefit people. unlike most books on urban planning, this is written by a journalist, and so contains charming stories that emphasize key points. overall, very easy to read, very interesting, and a great place to start for someone interested in urban design.

My Review: Dense, funny, and engaging. Intelligent, creative people who think they don't like math should read this and hopefully discover how cool may actually is as both a subject and a way of thinking. Kudos, Jordan Ellenberg.

Title: Driving Honda: Inside the World's Most Innovative Car Company

My Review:
Really liked this book. Even though I have followed the auto industry a little over the years, I had no idea how different Honda is as a car company, or the importance of its various innovations.

The author slipped a lot of personal ideas into the book as well, especially about globalization and other trade issues; these removed the book from its thesis a little bit. Also, the conclusion left much to be desired: it was about two paragraphs long, with very little to tie up the loose ends.

Overall though, this was a great read.

Title: Zero to One: Notes on Startups, or How to Build the Future
Author: Peter Thiel
My Review: This is such a great book! From the interesting concept of modern indefinite optimism to the seven things companies need to succeed, there is a lot of candid, interesting information in here. The subtitle saves the book: this is not necessarily a book about building startups. Rather, it is about startups and a whole lot of well-thought-out ideas to make our future world better. As a budding economist, I found it hard to swallow the idea, that competition is bad for both business and consumers, that drives so much of the rhetoric about the benefits of monopolization. Fortunately, I recognize the business sense behind it: more competition = lower profit, almost universally. Overall, I really enjoyed the candor and practical, enlightening commentary and analysis, notwithstanding all the "building a great future" tangents. Would recommend as a quick, easy read, unlike this review.

I would like to have had examples of how to invigorate a fraternity instead of assuming a stable status quo, but since it caters to your average fraternal audience and I understood that before getting book, I cannot complain. A solid four stars.

Title: The Chapter President: Preparing Sorority and Fraternity Leaders for the Unexpected
Author: Patrick Daley
My Review: Outlines what to do in forty situations that a chapter president is apparently commonly faced with. Better and more specific advice than the The Fraternity Leader, but still a little bit of a "better than you" tone popping up here and there. The first half is especially good.

Title: Out of Our Minds: Learning to Be Creative
Author: Ken Robinson

Title: Million Dollar Consulting: the Professional's Guide to Growing a Practice
Author: Alan Weiss

Title: The 4-Hour Workweek
Author: Timothy Ferriss
My Review:
I like the idea behind this book: increase productivity by focusing on the things that really matter, then escape from the meaningless rush for power and money by creating an automated self-sustaining business that requires little effort but yields great profits; this enables you to go travel and see the world and do things that you really love. I love the "Beg for forgiveness, don't ask permission" mentality and use it quite often. I think that things such as freeing yourself from office presence, justifying work for its own sake, and proposing solutions instead of asking for them are great ideas.
What I don't like about this book are the borderline unethical methods suggested to accomplish such things. You can do all those things without the amount of deception and irrational risk-taking that Ferriss suggests. Also, he makes building a $10,000+/month "muse" business sound really easy and fast. It's simply not. Ideas are hard to come by. Really hard. Then, execution is just as hard or harder.
In conclusion, great ideas that can help a lot, but you'd get the same benefits ethically by reading and following Greg McKeown's Essentialism (a great, great book).

Title: Blink: The Power of Thinking Without Thinking
Author: Malcolm Gladwell
My Review: Kudos to Malcolm and the crew. This book, though wandering and irresolute in its presentation, was a fascinating read. I really enjoyed the stories and examples, notwithstanding their occasional irrelevancy. Blink is so much better than the Tipping Point.

Title: Goals!: How to Get Everything You Want Faster Than You Ever Thought Possible
Author: Brian Tracy

Title: The Game: Penetrating the Secret Society of Pickup Artists
Author: Neil Strauss
My Review: Wow. A lot of good psychology stuff here, intertwined with a fascinating tale taking the reader deep into the lives of very interesting people. Of course, there is also a lot of pretty messed up womanizing, but hey, you know, whatever. Excellent read for any heterosexual male, or a shocker for anyone else.

Title: Tulipomania: The Story of the World's Most Coveted Flower & the Extraordinary Passions It Aroused
Author: Mike Dash
My Review: Tulipomania is a great book that satisfied the curiosity that A Random Walk Down Wall Street originally gave me.  Dash stays objective, mostly, and exhibits a great depth of research while letting the short length of the time period described dictate a short book length. The book remains focused on the tulip nearly the whole time, describing the history and events related to it with clarity and conciseness. I emphasize this because I didn't want to spend the better part of a week learning about a flower (though it is fascinating) when a shorter work is sufficient. I especially enjoyed the sections on the Ottoman Empire and the various savage whims of its violent, flower-loving rulers (a strange combination indeed).

Title: The Immortal Life of Henrietta Lacks
Author: Rebecca Skloot

Author: James Allen
My Review: Great. Like a more personal, secular combination of The Secret and existentialism. Very conscious of the state of humanity.

It changed my way of thinking about the concepts of good versus evil, enemies versus friends, and what war means for the relatively helpless pawns of the governments.

Author: Ricardo Semler

Title: The Idiot
Author: Fyodor Dostoyevsky
My Review: Fyodor, I loved reading your book. I really did. You display a masterful ability to convey the complicated emotional dynamics of a really weird eighteenth-century social group of dramatic Russian aristocrats. Your writing makes scenes and characters come alive in my mind. I never could have thought that Russia would have been so exciting all the time. However, [and Fyodor, don't take this the wrong way] your book didn't really grab hold of me. It didn't pull me in to the point where I put it down with great remorse. The characters were exciting and you made them come to life, but there didn't really seem to be any point to any of the things that they were doing. You conjured one mindless drama after another, and portrayed poor Myshkin as an idiot. Fyodor, Myshkin doesn't belong in your book at all! He is arguably the perfect man (though admittedly somewhat confused love-struck, and prone to anxiety attacks and illogical decisions). He is a shining pearl tossed about in a sea of dishonest, unstable, manipulative, and ungracious alcoholics. The problem is, you gave all those other characters too much sway in the plot. Myshkin needed to be a hero and achieve some great emotional victory and marry Aglaia (before she went completely crazy) and go live up in the mountains where the sun always shines! Instead, you just left him to fight off the pointless dramas that the other characters constantly managed to involve themselves in. I cannot say that I did not enjoy reading you book, Fyodor. But you just wrote the wrong one.

Title: The Girl Who Played with Fire (Millennium, #2)
Author: Stieg Larsson
My Review: OMGGGGGGGGGGG! So, normally I do not get very emotionally involved in the books I read. This is partly because I read a lot of nonfiction, and partly because I am just not a super emotional person. That being said, this book had me hanging on a thread off the edge of a cliff the whole time! Ahhh! Never before have I reacted so enthusiastically/violently to huge plot reveals. The story is incredible well-thought-out. There were four instances where I couldn't hold it in, and jumped off my bed and ran around the house yelling about some plot twist or another, jumping up and down, and repeatedly expressing my disbelief. My roommates just laughed, because they too had experienced the emotional roller coaster Stieg Larsson creates. So, to sum it up, I read this book in a day, got super engaged in the plot, and definitely rate it as one of the most exciting and hair-pulling books I have read (...though the endless stream of cigarettes is a little tiring). Well, played, Stieg, well played.

Title: Moneyball: The Art of Winning an Unfair Game
Author: Michael   Lewis
My Review:
I would be remiss if I gave this book anything less than five stars. The book combines the excellent writing of one of my favorite authors, Michael Lewis, with my favorite aspect, statistics, of my favorite sport, baseball. There is nothing not to like. I absolutely enjoyed reading this book. I decided to finally read it after all this time, even though I have basically memorized the story from secondary sources and know all the statistical aspects of the book from my obsessive following of sabermetric-minded baseball reporters. I love how Lewis paints the rational approach to the game as the obvious one, and constantly shoots off-hand criticism in the direction of the mindless, traditional baseball insider "club". Lewis' afterword and epilogue are even more amusing and offer a candid look at the ridiculousness of some aspects of the media and professional sports world. Totally recommend, A+, five stars, two enthusiastic thumbs up.

P.S. - I also got to write an eleven-page analysis paper on the book for a college statistics class, so I got to go really in-depth while reading and analyzing; despite reading it as an assignment, still like it. How could I not?

Title: Bad Feminist

My Review: This collection of essays is great, especially for me, as someone who hasn't read a lot about race or feminism. Gay relates both those topics to literature,  film, current events, and popular culture with provocative and surprisingly accessible style. I agree with much of what she says, and appreciate her perspectives on misogyny, race in the media, and reproductive rights (negotiability of the female body). I disliked three of the essays that didn't quite make sense to me and/or were too inflammatory in their arguments. Overall, though, Gay's unique style and perspective makes for a great book.

Title: A Connecticut Yankee in King Arthur's Court
Author: Mark Twain
My Review: This book is amazing. It is comical and educational, yet sobering and simultaneously informative. It is basically a  modern take on how to build a free society, but also explores human nature, historical tragedies, and especially the ridiculousness of medieval politics and the glorification of the Knights of the Round Table. With clever wit and skilled sotrytelling throughout, I'd say this book is Twain's best work and a must-read.

Title: Savage Inequalities: Children in America's Schools
Author: Jonathan Kozol
My Review: Savage Inequalities is pretty hollow. While it does a very good job at expressing the inequality of America's school system in poor urban areas as compared to wealthier suburbs, it fails to elaborate prescriptively except to endlessly drone on about money. Kozol basically posits that throwing money at a poor school will make it better. He also describes the school system as purposefully racist and segregated. He never mentions that schools are served by the people living around it; of course people living living in an extremely poor town are going to be poor and uneducated. He does recognize that property tax as a means to fund schools is wrong, and says that federal funding should replace it. However, the entire book essentially repeats itself; the only thing that ever changes is the location. After reading the book, I'm left feeling more aware of problems in inner city schools, but don't feel like i've gained anything else by reading it. Very disappointing book for me.

Title: Where Good Ideas Come From: The Natural History of Innovation
Author: Steven Johnson
My Review: I really enjoyed this book. Johnson spins an intricate web of Gladwell-esque narrative proportion, but without making it so easy to read that one becomes bored. Most of the ideas put forth are excellent, though there are a couple that could be considered somewhat redundant. The concepts of liquid networks, the adjacent possible, and exaptation are all intriguing and very intuitive. Luckily, it's not a dumbed-down self-help book; it simply presents patterns that assist in the creation and application of world-changing ideas. Overall a stimulating read for anyone who is interested in historical perspectives on innovation and/or is boredly interested by Malcolm Gladwell's books.

Title: How Children Succeed: Grit, Curiosity, and the Hidden Power of Character
Author: Paul Tough
My Review: Very good but without a very definable thesis. He switches from talking about the problems of child development to the success of mentoring to the importance of character, without tying ten together very we'll. however, each separate part of the book is very good if regarded as separate arguments. Solid and in depth examples throughout. Has a lot f research put into it obviously, lots of facts and figures that keep it interesting to stat nerds like me. It's not like a Malcolm Gladwell easy read; rather, it simultaneously remains intellectually stimulating and full if riveting narrative.
